article.description: Jason Richardson scored 24 points, Troy Murphy had 19 points and 13 rebounds and the Golden State Warriors snapped their four-game losing streak with a 109-99 victory over the Memphis Grizzlies on Wednesday night in Oakland, Calif.
article.headline: Golden State makes 11 threes
article.linkText: Warriors end 4-game skid with win over Grizz
article.story:
OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- In the closing minutes, Speedy Claxton ran the Golden State Warriors' offense flawlessly. His teammates made plenty of big shots and grabbed every big rebound as they firmly maintained their lead. Even coach Mike Montgomery was a bit stunned to see his young Warriors playing with such poise. Jason Richardson scored 24 points, Troy Murphy had 19 points and 13 rebounds and the Warriors snapped their four-game losing streak with a 109-99 victory over the Memphis Grizzlies on Wednesday night. Claxton scored 13 of his 22 points in the fourth quarter for the Warriors, who hit a season-best 11 3-pointers while rallying from an early 15-point deficit. "We could have easily folded, but we stayed right in it," Claxton said. "We really wanted this one. You want every one, but we needed this." Golden State maintained its lead through a tense fourth quarter, executing its offense and playing stifling defense on Memphis' best scorers. Even Montgomery, the Warriors' rookie coach, was unsure what sparked this encouraging burst of maturity in his 8-18 team. "We really came out aggressively, and I don't really know why," Montgomery said. "We needed that. The players did. I know the coaches did. (We) know we can compete in this league if we play like that." Murphy and Claxton hit back-to-back 3-pointers midway through the fourth to give the Warriors a 10-point lead. After Memphis cut it to 99-95 on Shane Battier's 3-pointer with 1:24 left, Richardson got behind the defense for a dunk, and Golden State made consecutive defensive stops to seal the win. Two nights earlier, the Warriors faltered down the stretch in a loss to Washington, allowing Gilbert Arenas' game-winning three-point play in the final second. "We've been getting better at the end of games all season long," Richardson said. "We've just got to continue to fight. Every game is going to be like this for us." James Posey scored 22 points for the Grizzlies, whose three-game winning streak was snapped. They beat both Los Angeles teams on back-to-back nights in their previous two games, but couldn't recapture that success up the California coast against the Western Conference's 14th-place team. "They picked us apart and made shots," Memphis coach Mike Fratello said. "They shot it well from the 3-point line, and the 35 free-throw attempts, that's just us not getting a defensive stance, not moving your feet, not making a commitment to stop people." Pau Gasol had 19 points and Stromile Swift added 18 points and eight rebounds, but Memphis made 21 turnovers and struggled to find open shots from its set offense in the final minutes. Jason Williams had 13 points and 11 assists -- just his first double-double of the season. Memphis dropped to 0-5 during Fratello's three-week tenure when allowing more than 90 points. The Grizzlies are 7-0 when holding opponents under 90. After trailing big in the first half, the Warriors ended the third quarter on a 22-7 run. Richardson had nine points in the rally, and Golden State took the lead on Eduardo Najera's third 3-pointer of the season. "At the beginning of the third quarter, we kind of stopped working," Gasol said. "The crowd woke up and they got confident and started making all kinds of shots, and we weren't as sharp as we were in the first half." Golden State and Memphis are two of the NBA's lowest-scoring teams, but their third meeting in six weeks featured a handful of spectacular shots and dunks, including a breathtaking windmill slam in the third quarter by Richardson, the two-time NBA dunk champion. Grizzlies assistant coach Eric Musselman was cheered in his return to Oakland, where he was the NBA's youngest head coach with the Warriors during the previous two seasons. He was fired last summer despite leading Golden State on the best two-year run in the last decade.

Game notes
The game was delayed briefly in the first quarter while a shattered candy cane was cleaned off the court. ... Battier briefly left the game in the first half to get two stitches above his right eye. ... Golden State got just nine rebounds in the first half, but 13 in the third quarter. ... Warriors F Mike Dunleavy sat out with the flu. Mickael Pietrus made his second start of the season in Dunleavy's place.
